[start section id="20112"]

#1 Stage IIIA, recently-diagnosed, poorly-differentiated colon cancer
Dr. Barta and myself explained to the patient that the patient does have a focus of micrometastasis in one of the lymph nodes.  The prognostic value of micrometastasis is not clearly established, but the patient will fall into the stage of T3, N1a.  We explained to the patient that with surgery alone, there is around a 50% chance of cure.  With adjuvant chemotherapy, there would be an additional 15% to 20% benefit of five-year survival and cure.  We explained to the patient that currently there is no evidence of metastatic disease and that his CEA level was normal.  The patient and family prefer to have the treatment locally at Catawba in Ellison Bay Ohio.  We will contact one of the oncologists there to start therapy.  We explained to the patient that the first-line of therapy would be modified FOLFOX6 regimen.  Side-effects of FOLFOX including peripheral neuropathy, diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, and stomatitis were explained to the patient.  The patient will also need a MediPort placed.
#2 History of prostate cancer in 1996, status-post prostatectomy and radiation therapy, in remission

[end section id="20112"]

